In an emergency call, the professor confessed to shooting his girlfriend
During a call to the emergency line with a trembling voice, Professor Shannon Lamb confessed to police that he had shot his girlfriend and it is necessary for them to come to their home.
Lamb resolved that his "sweet little dog" was alive and probably upset at the house, and that contacts to the family of the dead woman could be found on her phone.
Inside, police found the body of Amy Prentiss and a handwritten message on white office paper: "I am so sorry and wish I could return it, I loved Amy and she is the only one who has ever loved me," the letter said.
There was no suspicion that Lamb, who taught two online courses for Delta State University in Cleveland, Mississippi, would drive 300 miles to the school campus where police believe he shot popular professor Ethan Schmidt at his office door.
Delta State University police chief Lynn Buford said university staff heard the shooting at 10:18 a.m.
Lamb reportedly made a fateful call to an emergency line shortly thereafter.
Eventually, another death came; Lamb took his own life when the police came for him.
The day after the school shooting forced students and faculty to hide behind locked doors, the authorities are still trying to figure out what Lamb's motivation was.
The details released by state investigators and the students and staff who knew him together created an image of a talented but likely troubled teacher.
The students confirmed that they were looking forward to his lessons.
Police in Gautier, where Prentiss died, confirmed that he had no criminal record or violent past.
Schmidt himself included Lamb in a book he wrote, in a thank you to the "great people" with whom he shared an academic life.
Both taught at the Faculty of Social Sciences and History along with 17 other faculty members, and many students took courses at both at the same time.
At the same time, there were inclinations when it came to problems.
The student who praised Lamb, Brandon Beavers, said he also seemed agitated and shaky, "as if something were wrong with him."
Another student, Mikel Sykes, said Lamb told him he was struggling with stress at the end of the 2014-15 academic year.
Lamb had previously asked Delta State University for leave on medical grounds, saying he had a problem.
And this year, he only taught two online courses.
Recent changes to the university's staff recruitment meant that a doctorate that Lamb had worked hard on would not have guaranteed him an automatic tenure to become an assistant professor.
William LaForge, president of the university, said that he knew of no conflict between Lamb and Schmidt, but that "Mr Lamb was obviously troubled by something."
Lamb won't answer those questions anymore.
After leaving campus, police caught his trail as he crossed the Arkansas state border back to Misissippi.
Before he could be arrested, Lamb killed himself with a single pistol shot in the courtyard of his home about a mile from his parents in the suburbs of Greenville, Mississippi, Washington state coroner Methel Johnson confirmed.
He left the car on the street.
It was not immediately clear why Lamb was driving to this house, although Johnson said he probably knew the people who lived here.
Lamb grew up in this county.
Lamb began working at the university, which has 3,500 students in a city of about 12,000 inhabitants, in 2009 and taught geography and education classes.
In the spring he received his doctorate in education.
One of Lamb's longtime friends described him as a smart, charismatic and funny person.
Carla Hairston said she was 15 and Lamb was 20 when they met through mutual friends.
She was with her friends in high school and he was the great older guy who tutored her on guitar for several years.
He was quite the heartbreaker at the time.
The hearts of all the girls were scarred as soon as he showed up," said Hairston, who is now 40 and lives in the suburbs of Jackson.
Lamb and Prentiss reportedly dated for some time.
During an emergency call, Lamb said, "I killed my wife," but the marriage record never existed.
They had a dog named Lightning who lived with them in a brick house adjacent to the arm of the Gautier River.
Police said the dog was fine.
Prentiss' ex-husband, Shawn O'Steen, said they broke up 15 years ago, but remained friends and had a daughter, who is now 19.
"She was completely collapsed," O'Steen said of his daughter.
She was the best friend with her mother.
O'Steen said he had not met Lamb, but through his daughter Abigail he knew that Lamb was interested in music and played the blues.
Lamb met Prentiss when he and Abigail were studying at a summer festival three years ago.
Later, they played random gigs together.
O'Steen said his daughter writes and sings her own music.
Prentiss was a nurse who worked for various online companies.
Mike Shaffer, bartender and occasional entertainment coordinator at The Julep Room, a dimly lit bar near Gautier, said he last saw Lamb and Prentiss on the night of September 5, a pot that Lamb had finished playing guitar and harmonica for a small crowd.
There was no sign of anything bad.
“They were a happy couple,” he said.
We played and played each other a joke.
I mean, they both had a good sense of humor.
Schmidt, a slain professor, led a first-year seminar specializing in Native American and colonial history, said Don Allan Mitchell, an English professor at the school.
He was married and had three small children.
He studied at Emporia State University in Kansas and was president of the boys' student club and student government.
At the Delta State campus in Cleveland on Tuesday night, about 900 people including faculty members, staff, students, and community members attended a candlelight commemorative event.
Schmidt's wife Liz, and brother Jeff Schnidt also attended the vigil, during which the university choir sang "Bright Morning Star" and "Amazing Grace."
School started again on Wednesday.
"We're trying to get our students back," LaForge says.
The crisis is behind us.
This is a day of healing.
