8 election numbers that show Donald Trump in real light
Some have tried to describe him as a person who often changes his mind.
The others waved their hands like a joke.
And some are preparing for implosion.
But whether some Republicans are trying to pull Donald Trump down from the top of the election, they are failing (yet).
10 of the last 11 national polls show that Donald Trump is in the lead by a two-digit number, and some people are starting to seriously question what this means for the nomination chances of this real estate tycoon.
Of course, this is just the beginning of the election cycle.
None of this says Trump is likely to win the Republican nomination.
Experts point out that at this time in 2011, Rick Perry's leadership made way for Herman Cain's ascension, in the end, neither of them won a single position in the nomination process.
There are many reasons why he might run into a general election.
But outside groups like Jeb Bush’s Super PAC and the conservative economic group Club for Growth are aware of Trump’s will to endure and are starting to put their dollars on hold to bring him down.
Here are some recent poll numbers that suggest the real estate tycoon is not just a passing phase:
Trump’s approval rating has gone 180 degrees.
Just before Donald Trump announced his candidacy in mid-June, a Monmouth University poll showed that only two out of 10 Republicans had a positive view of the real estate tycoon.
By mid-July, it was 40%.
At the beginning of August, it was 52%.
Six out of 10 Republicans now have a favorable view of Donald Trump.
About three in 10 say they have a negative opinion of him.
And these numbers are held in the initial stages.
A Quinnipiac poll last week found that 60 percent of Republicans had a positive opinion of Trump.
Two-thirds of GOP voters would be satisfied with Trump as a candidate.
In a CNN/ORC poll conducted last week, 67 percent of Republicans said they would either be “enthusiastic” or “satisfied” with Trump as a candidate.
Only two out of 10 said they would be "indignant" at his candidacy.
Only Ben Carson creates roughly the same level of enthusiasm as Trump (43 percent of people said they would be “enthusiastic” against 40 percent saying the same about Trump).
The next closest in level of enthusiasm?
Marco Rubio with only 21%.
On the other hand, 47 percent of Republican voters say they would be "disappointed" or "excited" if the business favorite Jeb Bush became a candidate.
Most Republicans don’t see Trump’s temperament as a problem.
While Donald Trump has been widely criticized for his pomp and insults, 52 percent of Republican voters are nationally inclined to the idea that the real estate magnate has the right temperament for the presidency, according to Monday's ABC News/Washington Post poll.
The same figure holds at the Iowa State Senators' Club, which is the first in the country where 52 percent of Republicans think it has the personality of a commander, according to last week's Quinnipiac.
Still, 44 percent think he doesn’t have the personality to serve effectively, and nearly 6 in 10 independents say his temper doesn’t belong in the White House, according to ABC/Post.
Republican voters are getting used to the idea.
When he puts on his scholarly hats, Republican voters think Trump is a real candidate.
When asked who would most likely win the GOP nomination, four out of 10 said Trump would be the best choice, according to a CNN/ORC poll last week.
This is a change from late July, when four out of 10 were betting their money on Jeb Bush.
Full disclosure: GOP voters did not have the brightest crystal ball in the past.
By this time in the last cycle, 4 out of 10 Republicans had chosen Rick Perry as the winner of the candidacy against 28 percent for eventual nominee Mitt Romney.
Yet a certain number of GOP voters seem to view the Trump campaign as credible.
Even though Republicans have rallied around another candidate, Trump still beats almost everyone.
Some scholars point out that a fragmented field likely contributes to Trump's leadership, while anti-Trump support is diffused among more than a dozen other candidates.
But a survey by Monmouth University in early September shows that in the hypothetical direct fight between Trump and most other Republican candidates, Trump almost always gains majority support.
He leads Carly Fiorina by 13 points, Marc Rubio by 14 points, Walker by 15 points, Jeb Bush by 19 points and finally Rand Paul, John Kasich, Chris Christie by 33 points each.
He's in a dead race with Ted Cruz.
The only candidate who can beat him?
Ben Carson would lead the dealer by a wide 19 points in a hypothetical one-on-one match.
The vast majority of Donald Trump supporters say they have already made up their minds.
A new CBS/NYT poll Tuesday shows that only more than half of voters who support Trump say they won’t change their minds.
Obviously, a lot of things can change that, and no one can really say that he would never change his mind.
Forty-six percent said they keep their back door open for change among candidates.
Still, Trump’s current strongest opponent is his outsider colleague, neurosurgeon Ben Carson, but voters who consider their view final would be twice as likely to vote for Trump.
Six out of 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration.
Even since Donald Trump called immigrants from Mexico “rapists” in his campaign’s announcement speech, immigration has still held as the main and central topic of conversation for 2016.
Some fear that Trump’s pomp will draw key Hispanic voters away from the Republican Party and damage efforts to rebrand.
But according to a new Monday poll by ABC/Post, six out of 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration issues.
As long as immigration remains in the spotlight, Donald Trump will remain, too.
Frustration from the government is reaching new highs.
Today, Donald Trump and Ben Carson receive roughly half of the support from Republican voters, largely due to their status as outsiders.
Six out of 10 Republicans in a new ABC/Post poll on Monday say they want a political outsider rather than someone with government experience.
And they're also very angry at Washington.
A vote by the Des Moines Register/Bloomberg in Iowa a few weeks ago revealed that three out of four Republicans in Iowa are frustrated by Republicans in Congress, 54 percent are "disgruntled" and 21 percent "hellishly angry."
The House supported a greater share of the state's coal fees.
The Czech Republic will receive more than 400 million.
