Minister Jan Mládek (Czech Social Democratic Party - ČSSD) promised MPs that they would get extra money from both the state treasury and municipal budgets.
The bill has been criticised by opposition MPs, who fear that mining firms will no longer want to sponsor municipalities as they have been since they will pay higher fees directly to the state budget.The House at first reading supported the government's amendment to the mining bill, which means, among other things, that the state should receive a greater share of the revenue from brown coal surface mining fees from the mining company.
The share of the state will increase to 67 percent, while the share of municipalities will decrease from 75 percent to 33 percent.
The template also changes the way the payment for minerals mined by companies is calculated.
The change in fees for mining is expected to bring CZK 427 million more to the state treasury than in 2013.
According to the government, the revenues of municipal budgets should have a neutral impact, because the fee should be higher.
