The explanatory memorandum states that, according to mining companies, the increase in fees will not be reflected in coal prices, because prices are more than 90 percent long-term negotiated.
Therefore, major consumers such as power plants or heating plants should not feel the price increase.
"On the other hand, this fact increases the risk that mining organizations will compensate for the increase in payments by trying to reduce their operating expenses, which would primarily mean a reduction in the number of employees," the government admits.
However, in her view, the increase in fees is acceptable in terms of employment.
According to the rapporteur on the amendment, Milan Urban (ČSSD), it is crucial for MPs to know the conclusions regarding the updated energy concept and, in particular, the government’s decision on the limits of coal mining before the law is passed.
If coal is mined beyond the limits, then it will have impacts on revenues for the state and municipalities, he stressed.
Urban disagrees with Mládek that the decision to break the limit at the mine of the Czechoslovak Army should be made only after 2020.
