Jeremy Corbyn to debut at Prime Minister's Questions
Since his election, Mr. Corbyn’s PMQ debut has been highly anticipated.
New working leader Jeremy Corbyn will make his Prime Minister's Questions debut later, and will have to work with David Cameron for the first time.
Mr Corbyn will ask the first of his six assigned questions shortly after noon, while his performance is likely to be scrutinised carefully by the media and Members.
In a weekly statement, he demanded "less theatre and more facts."
He also stated that he could skip several sessions that he would leave to his colleagues.
This meeting will be the first parliamentary test of Mr Corby's leadership to come after his appointment to the Shadow Cabinet and his speech to the TUC Annual Congress on Tuesday.
Meanwhile, the Labour leader's decision to stand in silence while singing the national anthem on duty on Tuesday to mark the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Britain has been met with criticism from a number of Conservative MPs and is the focus of several front-page stories.
Mr Corbyn's decision not to sing the national anthem drew attention to himself
A spokesman for Mr Corbyn said he would "stand in respectful silence" and that he would recognise "the heroism of the Royal Air Force in the Battle of Britain."
However, a member of Mr Corbyn's shadow cabinet, Owen Smith, told BBC Two's Newsnight that he would recommend the Labour leader sing the national anthem "irrespective of" his belief that the monarchy should be abolished.
Nearly a dozen shadow ministers refused to serve on Mr Corbyn's top team, citing differences in economics, defense, and foreign affairs, and only less than a sixth of the parliamentary party initially supported him as leader.
BBC political correspondent Robin Brant says that political differences in work are also being "stored up" after Mr Corbyn's appointment despite his position in the European Union and the government's limit on benefits.
Mr Corbyl stated at the TUC conference that the Workers' Party had put forward amended proposals to remove the whole idea of the dose limit.
Hours later, Mr. Smith, secretary of shadow labor and pensions, stated that the party had "very clearly" opposed government plans to lower the limit from $26,000 to $23,000.
Mr Corbyn will be the fifth Labour Party leader David Cameron has faced in decades since his election as leader of the Conservatives.
The Labour Party leader, who promised a different approach to politics, claims to have "out of the crowd" ideas on questions for Mr Cameron and has received more than 30,000 proposals.
MP Islington North argues that PMQs are too confrontational and that they refrain from both "smooth answers," and toothed trade, and instead promises to focus on important issues such as poverty, inequality, and the challenges facing young people.
Mr. Corbyn claims Angela Eagle, the shadow trade secretary, will represent him at PMQ if he doesn't attend - such as when Mr. Cameron travels abroad.
He also dropped the idea of letting other colleagues speak for him from time to time, saying he had discussed the matter with House Speaker John Bercow.
When Mr Cameron became leader in 2005, he said he wanted to move away from the "Punch and Judy" style of politics that was often associated with PMQ, but he admitted a few years later that he had failed.
