Multiple sclerosis: it is not only the medication that matters, but also the patient's will to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complicated disease, and a person with this diagnosis needs the care of a number of specialists: neurologist, physiotherapist, occupational therapist, urologist, ophthalmologist, psychologist, psychiatrist and many other specialists.
However, it is not just about medical care, for example, women with multiple sclerosis also need consultations, if they decide to have a child, care for these patients includes social-legal advice, recommendations for adjusting housing, etc.
Yet all this is not enough: the development of the disease can fundamentally affect the patient himself.
The more she actively fights the disease, the longer she can work and does not have to fundamentally change her lifestyle.
As the doctors point out, the passivity of patients frees up space for disease activity.
For example, it has been proven that regular exercise significantly delays the time when the patient needs some compensatory aid, such as a cane.
It is important that patients and their surroundings are not subjected to various myths, for example, that the disease automatically leads them to end up in a wheelchair.
That is why the Give Yourself a Chance website (www.bezmytu.cz) was created, which is supported by the ongoing media campaign Give Yourself a Chance.
The most important person in the care of a patient with multiple sclerosis is a neurologist.
In the case of multiple sclerosis, there is a saying twice that the earlier the disease is treated, the more likely it is to affect the doctor.
This is because we have multiple sclerosis drugs in the inflammatory stage, when the neurodegeneration process is not yet as strong.
The sooner we intervene, the greater the chance that we will be able to stop the disease and delay disability, explains Dr. Eva Medová from the Neurology Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague.
Rehabilitation care is very important for people with multiple sclerosis, which most often addresses weakening of the lower limbs or balance disorders.
Patients are treated according to their individual needs: to maintain fitness, improve walking, strengthen the pelvic floor, reduce swallowing disorders or improve coordination.
"It's really individual, it depends on the specific problems of the patient," says Martina Kovari, MD, head of the Department of Rehabilitation and Sports Medicine at Motol University Hospital.
Although people with multiple sclerosis suffer from the same disease, it manifests itself in a slightly different way for everyone.
Rehabilitation can not stop the disease, but it can always relieve its symptoms.
However, physical activity also strengthens the immune state of the body, which is desirable in the case of multiple sclerosis.
Another positive of regular exercise is that patients check what they can do, and this strengthens their confidence.
"Exercise also leaches endorphins and one feels good after it," points out PhDr. Kamila Řasová from the Department of Rehabilitation Medicine at the University Hospital Královské Vinohrady.
By affecting the physical side, we affect the limbic system responsible for emotions.
We directly interfere with the psyche and immune processes and stabilize the disease, he adds.
"Previously, these patients were so-called sparing, today we know that they need a targeted load," says Prof. PaedDr. Pavel Kolář, head of the Rehabilitation and Sports Medicine Clinic at Motol University Hospital.
The goal of physiotherapy is to be able to remain self-sufficient for as long as possible, including at work.
Physiotherapists therefore cooperate with occupational therapists so that each person receives a compensation aid tailored to him.
Many patients also need the care of a psychologist or psychiatrist.
They are in a difficult life situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, most people shake it.
They experience shock, panic, fear.
It must respond to a great burden - the loss of health.
With such a sore soul, we should go to someone, not try to carry everything on our own shoulders.
"I work with them to eventually come to the conclusion that even with a disability one can live a full life and that multiple sclerosis does not mean the end of life," says psychotherapist Renata Malinová - Schubertová from the Neurology Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague.
Without the Prague manufacturer Latecoere, airplanes would not fly.
Aviation production is synonymous with precision and advanced technology.
New aircraft are full of titanium or light and solid composite materials, which can not be produced and processed right away.
Yet, in addition to super-precision, computer-controlled machine tools, along with autoclaves for shaping composites, it is possible to come across something as ordinary as apricot stones.
In the drum, which resembles a cotton candy pot, the edges of the sheet metal parts that just came out of the milling machine are plastered in a pile of pits.
"No one has come up with anything better yet," smiles Ivan Dubský, CEO of the aircraft door manufacturer Latecoere Czech Republic.
On the premises in Prague Letňany Letov produces complete doors for Airbus A320.
They are the only ones in the world to supply doors for the Brazilian Embraer 170.
Passengers entering the first and higher class on the upper decks of the world’s largest passenger aircraft, the Airbus A380, also enter through the doors, part of which is assembled in Prague.
There are also composite doors for the new Boeing 787 Dreamliner.
Accuracy is the main motto here.
For example, the company has the torque wrenches adjusted twice a year.
If the yellow sticker is missing a record of the inspection, they should explain in the Prague plant to auditors from Airbus or Boeing, who regularly travel to check whether the doors are manufactured according to the agreed rules.
However, advanced technology has not completely replaced the human senses.
There are 1,500 rivets on one door to the A320.
The riveters have to shake them by hand.
It takes them two days.
Even by the sound of the hammer hitting, they will know if the rivet is already shaken correctly.
The tolerance in which they operate is minimal.
Rivets can rise above the surface of the aircraft from zero to 0.13 millimeters.
That's about twice the thickness of a human hair.
During the inspection comes a trained touch.
When a controller runs his finger over a row of rivets, he can tell if one is out of tolerance.
Then he picks up the exact dial.
Before 1989, Letov supported the L-39 military training aircraft program.
In 1991, none of them were built.
The company had to find new contracts quickly.
At the time, it was partnered with European aircraft manufacturer Airbus.
She won a tender for the emergency door supplier for the A321.
The Boeing deal wasn't so happy.
“We were a small company that didn’t have enough money to invest and to guarantee Boeing long-term stable deliveries,” Dubský said.
The door to the American manufacturer would have remained slammed if Letov had not attracted the French Latecoere group at the Prague conference of the international aviation industry association in 1999.
I was talking about our cooperation with Airbus.
Negotiations with the French began the next day, Dubsky said.
A year later, Latecoere bought the Czech company and with a strong company came new orders.
The assembly of door parts for the A320 started in 2000.
Three years later, the upper deck doors for the A380 were added.
In 2006, the company built a new composite processing hall to supply Boeing Dreamliner.
Without Latecoere, we would not be able to get these big contracts ourselves.
Maybe we'd make parts or small parts.
The partners want a guarantee of delivery for twenty or thirty years, Dubský explains.
Last year, the Czech Latecoere achieved turnover of over 2.9 billion and profit after tax of 147 million crowns.
The exclusive position among the suppliers of aircraft manufacturers is not free.
Latecoere has invested CZK 1.5 billion in Prague since 2000.
The company must have quality certificates, 170 specific production processes and certificates of qualification for key employees.
Without them, the company would not have built any aircraft doors.
According to Dubský, it costs millions of crowns to obtain certificates that the production processes meet the requirements of customers and to keep them in repeated inspections.
Production processes change every year.
They are more precise and strict.
We have to train the employees, retrofit the equipment and re-certify the whole process, Dubský adds.
Now, the company is finalizing the process for zinc and nickel plating to replace the previously harmful cadmium.
They received the assignments from the manufacturer, but then had to adapt the technology to the equipment or chemicals they use in Prague.
The people from Boeing will come and test the concept of the entire line.
Then we'll show them the production.
They'll also check our lab.
They test one set of samples themselves in their laboratory and then compare the results with ours, explains Dubský the way the customers check them.
The reward is Prague company’s long-term exclusive contracts.
With the Prague plant, embraer production stands and falls today.
For the A320, it produces half of the total volume of the doors.
Replacing the Czech Latecoere is either impossible or very difficult for a Brazilian or European manufacturer.
However, this does not mean that you can ask for any price at the door.
The contract includes a price curve.
This indicates how much one door will cost by ten, fifty, hundreds of pieces.
The price per piece keeps falling to a certain limit value.
We have to fit into this price formula.
If not, we will lose, says Dubsky.
Half of the hall where the electric boxes for the Airbus A400 M military aircraft are assembled is empty.
It is a symbol of the future.
A new semi-robotic riveting and door assembly line is being built behind the screen for the upgraded A320 Neo.
Riveting will speed up and refine.
"This is the trend that assembly in aviation is taking," adds Dubský.
The future line is secured.
Airbus has ordered 3,278 new A320s so far.
Just a few meters away will be a line for the complete installation of the doors for the upper deck of the A380.
It is the strategic decision of our parent company.
The aim is to reduce production times and costs.
Full assembly could begin in two years, Dubský says.
Before that, however, the company has to pass qualification tests, for example, to mount some electrical and electronic equipment in the doors for the largest Airbus.
The company also relies on the further development of production from composite materials.
In addition to Boeing, it is also expected to participate in the new Airbus A350 program, which will compete with the American Dreamliner.
“It is a huge credit for the company to be able to process composites in addition to metal materials,” Dubský proudly says.
However, Latecoere is on the edge of production capacity in the Czech Republic.
There is no more room in the Letov area, where it is located.
The company had 180 employees before the French mother's accession.
Now it has 800, and in three years there could be hundreds more.
As long as Airbus and Boeing are racing to see how many hundreds of new planes they order each year, they don’t have to worry about jobs.
Although he has orders for several years ahead, the parent company of Prague’s Latecoere faced the threat of bankruptcy.
The French group did not have enough money for September loan repayments.
In the end, Latecoere was able to negotiate with major lenders.
At the end of August, some of the loans were exchanged for shares.
Creditors acquired a share of 37.4% in the company by raising 57.4 million euros.
The company’s debt fell by two-thirds, i.e. by 180 million euros.
The second part of the financial recovery came in early September.
The company signed new shares among existing shareholders for 222.9 million euros.
In total, it increased the registered capital by 280 million euros.
The group benefits from growing production of Airbus and Boeing, which account for 85 percent of sales.
Average order growth is expected to increase by 4% per year until 2017.
In the order book, he has orders for 2.6 billion euros, which is equivalent to four years of production.
French media say Latecoere may finally be able to breathe again after years on the drips.
The Czech race in Letňany in Prague is important for groups.
It contributes 16% to the group’s sales.
According to the number of employees, it is the largest foreign branch of the group.
They supported a greater share of the state’s coal taxes.
The change in fees for mining is expected to bring CZK 427 million more to the state treasury than in 2013.
According to the government, the revenues of municipal budgets should have a neutral impact, because the fee should be higher.
Last year, municipalities received CZK 450 million in fees and the state budget CZK 150 million.
The mining of brown coal cost municipalities about CZK 200 million and the state CZK 66 million.
The amendment also envisages an increase in the payment from mining premises with permitted mining to one thousand crowns per hectare per year.
The income from these payments should continue to belong to municipalities in its entirety.
Minister of Industry Jan Mládek (ČSSD) told MPs that municipalities will gain CZK 14 million to CZK 100 million per year instead of CZK 14 million.
The amount of mining fees will no longer be determined by law, but will be set by the government by its regulation.
Reimbursement is newly calculated as the product of the amount of minerals mined and the rate for each type of mineral.
According to the government, the reason for the change is, among other things, the possibility of a flexible response to the current economic situation.
ODS MP Marek Benda warned that setting a fee by government decree may not be in accordance with the constitution.
According to Minister Mládek, however, this is not a tax because the state charges for the mineral, which is state property.
Fees are paid only to municipalities whose territories are affected by mining.
In the case of underground coal mining, three-quarters of the municipality’s money and a quarter of the state’s.
The same ratio will be in the case of the extraction of radioactive rocks.
The part of the money collected by the state in mining fees will be earmarked.
For example, 28 percent will have to go to repair damage after mining or to provide mining rescue services.
The draft was criticised today by opposition MPs, who claimed in particular that it would harm communities affected by mining and regions.
For example, Michal Kučera (TOP 09 and the Mayors) warned that mining companies will no longer want to sponsor municipalities as before, because they will pay higher fees directly into the state budget.
"It is not possible to tunnel one of the poorest regions just to have the finance minister improve his budget," said David Kádner (Dawn) elected in the Ústí Region.
KSČM MP Hana Aulická warned about the rise in unemployment in Mostek.
Kádner and Aulická unsuccessfully proposed to reject the amendment, Kučera wanted to return the law to the government for completion.
