Apple has a yo-yo effect.
It's all the displays.
A more powerful processor, a higher-resolution camera, a firmer chassis, and a touch-sensitive display are the advantages of the recently introduced ninth-generation iPhones.
The latter two also have a negative impact on the dimensions and weight of the iPhone 6s and 6s Plus.
So far, Apple’s trend has been that each new generation of iPhones is lighter than the previous one.
The only exceptions were the third and fourth generation, whose weight slightly increased compared to previous iPhones.
The two-gram weight difference in favor of the news was really negligible.
This is not the case with the new iPhones.
Compared to last year’s iPhones 6 and 6 Plus, the weight increased by 14 grams for a smaller model, and by 20 grams for a larger one.
Unsurprisingly, last year’s affair of bending in Apple’s pockets suffered greatly.
The chassis of the novelty is made of a more durable aluminum alloy 7000, which is also reflected in the weight.
But displays have a much greater impact on it.
Apple uses 3D Touch technology to recognize the power of touch.
To do this, the display had to be equipped with an additional layer of capacitive sensors.
The weight of the new iPhone displays has more than doubled compared to previous generations.
For a smaller iPhone, from 12 grams to 29 grams, for a larger iPhone, from 19 grams to 40 grams.
For iPhone 6s, the display is the heaviest component used.
The weight of just 143 grams is achieved thanks to the slimming bark, which has touched most of the remaining components.
In a larger model, the heaviest element used is the battery, but its weight has not changed compared to its predecessor.
Even in this case, the biggest increase is seen in the display.
The weight of the 5.5" iPhone 6s Plus is 192 grams.
As much as the new display technology will be practical, it will only take effect during use.
First users will be able to try it on Friday, September 25, when the iPhone 6s and 6s Plus will be launched in selected countries.
Have breakfast flakes been champions for tens of thousands of years?
In Grotta Paglicci, Italy, archaeologists have managed to find a find that opens up interesting possibilities.
They discovered traces of modern human settlement from different times, including murals, remnants of tools, and so on and so forth.
But in layer 23A, which according to the instruments is dated to about 30,000 years ago, scientists have discovered something that closely resembles the remains of a breakfast buffet.
Traces of oat grains were found on the site, which apparently went through the process of making today's so popular flakes.
Today, the grain is first soaked, then dried, removed from the packaging, called the plum, then steamed and flattened.
In the Paglicci cave, grains were discovered that seemed to have been heated or steamed, and then apparently crushed between two millstones - at least there are signs of use on two stones in the cave.
Thus, scientists have not been able to prove in their publication for the journal PNAS that there is a complete process of making flakes in the cave, but the similarity is really very noticeable.
We also have no evidence of how humans could have eaten flakes, but the assumption that it was with some liquid and quite possibly even warm is, of course, quite logical.
At the same time, it is a very interesting proof of how intensively people used cereals long before the emergence of agriculture.
If the flake interpretation is correct, the oldest flakes have overtaken agriculture by about twenty thousand years.
