The symbol of the village has come alive.
The wheel of the windmill above Chlum is turning again after years.
It can be seen from afar, as it is located on a 15-meter-high mast.
People from all over the world call it "the wind on Chlum".
For the village with 150 inhabitants, it became one of the elements of the municipal coat of arms that the village received on the occasion of the reunion of natives in 2010.
"We asked for a sign at that time and of course we wanted to have a fan on the sign, everyone knows it around," Mayor Jiří Mašek said.
The Chlum wind pump is a local technical monument.
It is also a memento of our time: it reminds us of a time when people were fighting for quality drinking water.
The one in Chlum in the past centuries was a rarity.
It was not until 1910 that the representatives of Chlum decided on a solution that was suitable until the mid-1980s.
A seven-meter deep well was dug in the village at the branch to Číchov.
Three years later, the well was completed with a metal structure with a wind pump, which drew water into the reservoir at the highest point of the village, near the local church.
"The construction was carried out by Antonín Kunc of Hranice na Moravě at a cost of 2,400 crowns," says a memorial inscription on the ground-floor fence of the mast structure.
The pump, after several repairs and falls of the wind wheel, was retired in 1971.
On May 7, 1973, a new chapter in the struggle for water began: on that day, a new water supply system began to serve in Chlum.
The wind pump has remained only a non-functional municipal symbol and a rarity here.
Dominance was put into operation at this year's native convention.
It was not until 2008 that Chlumští decided to repair the wind bike again and put it back into operation.
They had a replica of the original wheel made - reduced by an average of half a meter.
The wheel was mounted on the mast, but had to be brought down the same year.
The replica manufacturer did not choose the appropriate material and the wheel could not resist the gusts of wind.
Then the Chlum landmark rested for several years dismantled under the roof.
Since June this year, however, the wheel on the high mast is turning again.
On the occasion of the meeting of the natives, the village had the replica of the bicycle modified and replanted it on the top of the iron tower.
But the wheel only draws utility water from the well into the overflowing blind arm.
And over the summer, we completely disconnected it, because there was not enough water in the well.
At least it was empty.
"In the autumn, we will disconnect the wind wheel shaft from the pump in the suction basket again," said Mayor Mašek.
Chlum is not the only village in the Czech Republic where the wind bike has been included in the municipal coat of arms, but it is the only village of this kind in the whole Vysočina region.
They have a similar element in the coat of arms in honor of local technical monuments, for example, in Chvalkovice and Zelená Hora in the Vyškov region, in Kuželov in the Hodonín region, Partutovice in the Přerovsk region, or in the Police in the Vsetín region.
