No one explained to me how I should keep the refugees in the country if they do not want to live in the Czech Republic.
Czech Interior Minister Milan Chovanec (Czech Social Democratic Party - ČSSD) complains after talks with his European colleagues that other countries are pushing the Czech Republic to accept quotas for the redistribution of refugees, but rejects any discussion.
He also notes that no one has yet explained to him how he should keep the assigned refugees in the Czech Republic, if they do not want to live here anyway.
"We didn't get an answer, so we wanted the quotas to be removed from the final text," Chovanec told reporters.
Can you describe more specifically the position you came up with at the meeting of the Ministers of the Interior and Foreign Affairs of the European Union?
We do not agree with mandatory quotas as a system that simply cannot work.
We cannot refer to migrants as bags of salt or flour.
They are living beings who have some visions, they are going somewhere, they have some relatives.
We wanted to hear from colleagues how we are able to keep migrants on the territory of the Member States if they were redistributed.
We can't imagine.
We did not get an answer, and therefore we wanted the quotas to be deleted from the final text.
With the other conclusions - functional hotspots, i.e. registration points, border protection, camps outside Europe, the Trust Fund for African countries and other things - we have no problem with that.
We've been talking about this for a year, and we say this is the way to go.
But to say that quotas will solve everything?
We recently raised $40,000, now it's $120,000.
When will it be five hundred thousand?
And how do we keep these people in this territory?
Ninety-eight percent of all people who cross us want to go to Germany.
Almost no one wants to come to us, we just don’t know how to keep them here.
Other foreigners, Ukrainians, Vietnamese and others, who take the Czech Republic as a destination country, gain asylum with us, have ambitions to come to us, but the interest of people from this migration wave, i.e. from Syria and other countries, is limited to close to zero.
You mentioned that the refugees do not even want to come to us, but we have already committed ourselves to welcoming fifteen hundred people.
Would it not be possible to accept more of them this way?
We're committed to hiring 1,500 people, but with the condition.
We said: functional hotspots, border protection, military operation.
Even with the 1,500, there will be 1,100 people with whom we will deal with the asylum procedure.
They will come to our detention facility and we will treat them the same as the ones we captured.
It is a big question, and we will debate this with Europe, whether we can detain people who will be registered in Italy and Greece, or possibly Hungary.
Because Europe treats this so that if they have a registration, they cannot be detained.
That is, they will come to our territory with registration, and if there is an agreement, which is not yet, it may happen that even the 1100 will not be kept in the territory of the Czech Republic, and they will leave for Germany again when they arrive.
If we can detain them for the duration of the asylum procedure, we will deal with them in the asylum procedure.
If they are citizens of Syria, Eritrea, they will receive almost 98 percent of international protection, according to European statistics.
They will then be given documents that will allow them to travel around Europe.
And I think that these people will end up in the target countries again.
Then there are four hundred people who are going to be resettled.
This is the second project that is still underway, and we have made progress there only by debating with the churches about the possibility that they could help them get jobs, accommodation, and so on.
But that's a very long run.
You said that at the ministerial meeting other states were not willing to discuss with us.
But is it not the case that the Czech Republic only rejects quotas, but offers no solidarity to unblock the discussion?
What exactly do you think this is a solidarity move?
If the Federal Republic of Germany gives an incentive that all migrants from Syria can reach them, then the news spreads in hours throughout all camps in Europe, but also in Turkey, Jordan.
It calls for another wave of migration to Germany, because they simply do not want to come to us.
We think that the way is to protect the external borders - simply to deter the waves of migration, to help the needy, and to separate economic migrants.
Let them know that they don’t have a chance.
Last year alone, 50,000 Kosovars came to Germany.
From safe Kosovo, where we pay for all the saturation of this state, including the police, the courts, the prosecutors' offices.
If we managed to separate them and not accept them or accept them only according to the needs of the economies, the 50 percent of what the social systems are now spending on them in vain could go to refugees.
Compared to the first day when Germany introduced controls, the number of detainees in the Czech Republic jumped.
Now it's eighty, the first day it was twelve.
How far will it take to tighten up border controls?
We were afraid of hundreds of people.
These are the numbers we manage.
We still have a few hundred places available in stone detention facilities.
Of course, all the people we detain will be returned to Austria within seven days.
We do it as standard.
The Austrians are the only ones who take these people away from us, with Hungary it is complicated, and the Greeks - this is a completely useless story.
So where's the tipping point?
Would it have to be a thousand a day?
I think it would have to be several hundred a day.
Two, three hundred people a day for two, three days in a row will exhaust our capacities to the point that crisis plans will begin.
Then I agree with the Prime Minister that he would immediately convene an extraordinary government.
He is very interested in the whole thing, we are in contact by phone several times a day.
If the situation should arise, the government can sit de facto immediately and with one resolution it would decide to strengthen the police by the army, say, the customs administration, or possibly the prison service.
The extreme variant is the state of emergency that Hungary has now declared in some places?
I don't think we can get this far.
Remember that our position is different, we are a national state within Europe, we only have the Schengen border at the airport.
I do not know what would have to happen for this to happen in the Czech Republic, I do not want to spread alarm information.
All the information we have, whether from Moldova, Serbia, Hungary, suggests that Hungarians will try to divert migration flows to Croatia and Slovenia, which would then mean a direct trip to Austria.
The Czech Republic would be affected very marginally, almost at all.
