At its most anticipated meeting in years, federal reserve lawmakers will spend two days this week sitting at the 27-foot-long Honduran mahogany table, deciding whether it’s time to raise a key interest rate after nearly a decade.
Towering over them at one end of the central bank's ornament, the two-story meeting room will be a United States mural.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues are supposed to put the nation's economic interests above everything else.
The central bank has a double charge from Congress: to maximize U.S. employment and keep local prices stable.
But since the Great Recession, Fed officials have acknowledged that there is an unwritten third term: financial stability.
And this third term could be an X-factor too close to the predictable decision to be announced on Thursday whether the U.S. economy is ready to start weaning off an unprecedented stimulus in the form of near-zero short-term interest rates in place since late 2008.
Although much of the data shows solid economic growth, recent turbulence in world financial markets could scare the already cautious Fed into adding to volatility by raising its federal funds reference rate - no more than a quarter of a percentage point.
“Clearly, the labor market and inflation will be the most important thing to watch first,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"But I think they were just looking for an excuse not to increase the rate, the increased uncertainty surrounding the global market already provides them with sufficient justification to wait any longer," she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself is a cause for nervousness in financial markets.
About half of economists recently polled by Blomberg predicted a rate hike this week.
Financial markets, however, expect the Fed to stall the issue, with a key indicator of only about a 30% chance of an increase.
This would point to a fall in the stock market if the Fed raised rates only if policymakers softened the slump by promising no further increases.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average jumped 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The rally was triggered by expectations that Fed policymakers would hold back rates this week, says John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be a surprise if the Fed now raises rates," he said.
If Fed policymakers did, “they would have to go to extremes in their program statement and hold hands with the financial markets so they don’t panic.”
Other experts have argued that raising rates would calm financial markets, as it would remove uncertainty from how the Fed would proceed.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed on track to raise the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the US economic recovery.
Yellen said she expects rates to rise this year through spring and early summer despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress is needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, the labor market has seen solid growth this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% the previous month, the lowest in more than seven years, and is close to what the Fed considers full employment.
Wage gains showed signs of lift.
And while inflation continues to be below the central bank’s 2% annual target, Fed policymakers say the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the tightness in the labor market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world began to fluctuate late last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell as much as 16% below its record high in May as investors worried that China’s slowing economy would drag down global growth.
The market rebounded somewhat this month, and the Dow is now only losing nearly 10% of its May high.
The Fed’s turmoil in the market provides a comprehensive calculation of when to start raising interest rates.
"In the absence of what has happened in the financial markets, and of reports of weakness in the Chinese economy over the past few weeks, there would be tightening at this meeting," said Stephen D. Oliner, senior researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
He now predicts that they will wait at least a month to gain better control over the consequences.
