Weight loss surgery could be useful for moderately obese diabetics
The benefits of weight loss surgery for moderately obese people with type 2 diabetes can last for at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is still too early to tell whether moderately obese people with type 2 diabetes live longer after weight loss surgery than those receiving non-surgical treatment.
"The mortality figures take a long time to show," says Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in weight loss surgery who wrote an editorial for a new study on JAMA surgery.
Surgery for weight loss, bariatric surgery use different methods to shrink the stomach.
Reduce hunger and restrict the human body to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been shown to be effective for treating type 2 diabetes, but most of the survey was conducted on people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 25 or higher.
BMI, which measures the height-related weight relationship, is considered normal at values between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or higher indicates a person is overweight, and people with a BMI above 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For their new studies, researchers from Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected from a 2007 study that looked at two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass surgery and gastrectomy - in type 3 diabetes treatments for people who were moderately obese.
The average BMI of those who underwent surgery fell from 31 to 24.5 at the end of their fifth year, according to the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI of those who were not given diabetes surgery remained roughly the same at 29.
Among patients with surgery, diabetes was resolved completely in 36 percent and partially in 28 cases.
In the group treated, only 1 percent of the patients had diabetes, and only 2 percent had it.
Furthermore, control of blood pressure, triglycerides, and “bad” LDL cholesterol was shown to be “generally better in the surgical group,” the authors found.
The researchers also monitored the patient’s levels of hemoglobin A1c in the blood, which reflects continuous blood sugar levels in the body.
Hemoglobin A1c is best kept below 7%, the researchers say.
After surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c decreased from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
In the treated group, however, this figure remained at about 8 percent.
But this better "glycemic control" -- which is reflected in better hemoglobin A1c levels -- didn't reduce mortality at age five, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and his colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results with two types of operations.
After the fifth year, the bypass group lost more weight compared to the gastrectomy group (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), achieved greater decreases in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1 percent versus 2.1 percent), and were more likely to have diabetes remission (46.9 percent versus 16.7 percent).
While the new study does not show improvement in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of stronger people in Sweden, where they found that surgery leads to life extension, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona College or Medicine-Phoenix.
According to a Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery had about a 29 percent greater chance of survival over the next 15 years, compared to a group who tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not show improvement in survival among post-surgery patients, according to Blackstone, it is a calming result for people with a BMI below 35 who are interested in these procedures.
"This is where the work is critical because it states that surgery is safer in the lower BMI group," without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, he states.
Blackstone also claims that people and their doctors should start taking weight seriously after a patient’s BMI drops between 27 and 30.
“I think we’ve been waiting too long to let people know the seriousness of the situation,” he says.
