How the refugee crisis has shattered the Schengen area.
The emergency flare launched by Germany has far from cementing the European crew, but is already forcing the ship to change course, the French newspaper Le Figaro wrote.
The European Union decided on Monday to tackle the refugee problem first: it would be more likely to systematically sort migrants and asylum-seekers as they set foot on the old continent - especially in Greece - than to argue over the future distribution of refugees by quota based on the amount that is increasingly moving away from reality.
Six days after European Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker asked 25 of the 28 EU countries to redistribute 160,000 refugees, the interior ministers of the member states changed priority.
Before taking care of the final destination of the refugees, it is first necessary to filter out those who are arriving today and resolve the fate of those who are already moving within the Schengen area.
"Effective management of the EU's external borders is essential for managing migration," the ministers said in a text discussed in Brussels on Monday.
After the crisis of the common currency, the EU finds itself at risk in its next major integration project.
Germany may be surprised, but it does not lose its decisiveness and increases the pressure.
It restores border controls, especially with Austria, but without blocking the influx of those seeking asylum in that country.
The Central Power is thus making it clear that without it, no free movement in Europe is possible.
As evidence, Austria and Slovakia joined the measure on Monday.
Poland, the Netherlands, Belgium and even France are also considering this, albeit with varying intensity.
Hungary did this a long time ago.
These exceptional and temporary measures are permissible under Schengen rules.
It’s a domino effect, but it can also be seen by the blind.
A key issue for Berlin and Paris is now the effective introduction of mandatory entry controls in Greece, southern Italy and also Hungary for those who have already passed inland.
French Interior Minister Bernard Cazeneuve and his German colleague Thomas de Maiziere intensively discussed this during a private conversation with their three colleagues from Greece, Italy and Hungary.
This idea is not new, but it is being implemented.
In Italy, according to unofficial statistics, two-thirds of new arrivals have already been registered and identified with fingerprinting.
Budapest rejects the introduction of any entry point on its territory because it is more afraid than others that camps will remain on its shoulders in which refugees would accumulate at its expense.
The real black hole is Greece.
More than 200,000 people have landed on its islands near the Turkish coast this year, twice as many as have recently arrived in Italy.
Most of them are real asylum seekers who came directly from Syria after going through overcrowded camps in Lebanon, Turkey and Jordan.
It's a huge gaping hole.
Athens, which is still in financial turmoil and waiting for a new government, has put their hands in their laps.
This is the starting point for the Balkan route and a source of shared concern for German Chancellor Angela Merkel and Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orbán.
The Juncker Commission promises to implement the checkpoints as soon as possible, but has not given any number or date.
“The challenges facing Greece extend to the whole of Europe,” EU interior ministers agreed on Monday to mobilize on the front.
It is therefore a matter of deploying the intervention teams of the European border control agency Frontex in this country.
The EU wants to help Greece expand its reception capacity and strengthen its surveillance of the islands.
"Adequate financial resources will be needed," warns the text submitted to ministers for approval.
From a legal point of view, Athens will continue to have the final say.
The question of the creation of genuine European border guards has not been officially raised, but Europe is close to it.
The new emergency situation of the 28-nation bloc has already pushed back the issue of binding quotas and 160,000 refugees, which was raised earlier this year by the Juncker Commission and the European Parliament, and strongly supported by Angela Merkel and French President Francois Hollande.
Hungary, Slovakia, the Czech Republic and Poland still do not want to hear about it.
They see it as an attack on their sovereignty.
The number, but not the obligation, was retained on Monday in a text approved by a majority of 28.
But as a political commitment.
In other words, the process is interrupted.
The only firm pledge includes the redistribution of 40,000 refugees over the next two years, an agreement already reached in June during a hectic EU summit, Le Figaro concludes.
