In the event of bankruptcy, insurance companies are to pay the claims of clients in full.
Insurance companies should cover the claims of clients in the event of the travel agency’s bankruptcy in full.
This was decided by the House on Wednesday, when it approved an amended amendment to the law on the conditions of doing business in tourism.
According to the draft, travel agencies will be able to replace insurance against bankruptcy with a bank guarantee.
Insurance companies do not agree with the obligation to pay the claims of clients even above the agreed limit.
The Ministry of Regional Development insists on the adjustment, argues consumer protection.
Insurance companies have already threatened to stop insuring travel agencies against bankruptcy if the amendment goes into effect.
The proposal has also been criticised by travel agencies.
Without insurance, they will either have to quit or go abroad.
Regional Development Minister Karla Šlechtová (for ANO) pointed out that the cases where insurance companies did not pay full compensation are not Eurocomform.
She drew attention to this year's decision of the Constitutional Court, which confirmed that the client is entitled to a full refund, regardless of the insurance limit.
Insurance companies will receive enough information about the management of travel agencies and will be able to determine the correct limit, Šlechtová stressed.
"We appreciate the effort to increase consumer protection, but it must have such a limit that it is feasible," TOP 09 vice-chairman Miroslav Kalousek said.
The bank guarantee will not work because no one will give it unlimited.
"Travel agencies will have to stop their activities or move abroad," Kalousek warned.
A member of the Presidium of the Association of Czech Travel Agents Tomio Okamura (SPD) disagreed with Kalousek’s concerns based on a survey among members of the travel agency.
"Stop showing us lobbying by insurance companies," he said.
Okamura does not consider the insurance companies’ statements to be relevant and there is no official written statement to that effect.
However, they are trying to figure out whether travel agencies will be complicit, which, according to Okamura, is not a problem.
Jana Fischerová (ODS), who referred to the opinion of the rival Association of Travel Agencies of the Czech Republic, and her party colleague Petr Bendl, who spoke about deleting the stairs for Czech travel agencies, also warned about the provision.
According to Fischer, travel agencies will not be able to negotiate insurance.
"Consumer protection works," Fischer said.
Her motion to delete the disputed passage was not approved by the House.
Neither did Vojtěch Filip (KSČM) come forward with a proposal to return the draft to the committee due to an alleged violation of the Civil Code.
Philip warned of travel agencies that could pose a threat to consumers.
The rapporteur, Martina Berdychová (ANO), withdrew her proposal to limit the liability of insurance companies in cases where they could not have known that the insurance coverage would not cover the entire risk.
The amendment will not propose a minimum insurance limit of four million for travel agencies offering air travel and a million limit for offices selling, for example, bus tours.
The border will remain at 30 percent of the planned sales of tours.
However, the insurance coverage limit will have to be such that in the event of the travel agency’s bankruptcy, it will cover all customer claims.
Even after the modifications, the standard stipulates that travel agencies will have to newly indicate which travel agency organizes the tour for the sold tours.
Travel agencies will have to submit to the insurance companies, among other things, data on the economy and number of tours before concluding the contract.
The approved amendment of the Public Administration Committee also provides for further regular information to insurance companies.
Travel agencies will have to provide monthly data on the number of passengers and sold tours, the total price of sold tours and the amount of advance payments and sales for tours and vouchers.
If the Ministry of Regional Development finds that the travel agency has not fulfilled any of the statutory obligations towards the insurance company, it will ask the travel agency to remedy it according to the draft or will be able to prohibit it from entering into new contracts in the event that the breach of the obligation could endanger the interests of customers.
The amendment also provides for new financing for the mountain service.
The Ministry of Regional Development will determine the amount of the subsidy to the mountain service on the basis of its application, which will be submitted until the end of April for another year.
The application will include a report on the use of state money in the past year, a financial plan of expenditure and a outlook for the next two years.
According to the association, the law submitter did not think about what would happen if the insurance company terminated the contract.
It will not be allowed to organize tours, and clients who purchased the tour before the cancellation of the insurance, according to the association, will lose it.
In this case, CK will suffer a significant loss and may even go bankrupt, even though its management was in good shape.
One way travel agencies can cope with such a situation will be to sue the state for compensation.
Another option will be to go abroad and take advantage of much softer conditions abroad and then we will only operate in our market as agencies, said the vice-chairman of the association, John Pope.
According to him, the draft amendment also contains the institution of a bank guarantee, but so unthought-out that it cannot be implemented in practice at all, because the bank guarantee cannot sound for an unlimited amount.
Moreover, according to the association, the change of the current practice is de facto unnecessary.
