Xi calls for opening up the economy to the wider world
It is necessary to open the economy to the wider world to boost growth, President Xi Jinping told the group, whose task is Tuesday's management reform.
"China should engage in attracting foreign investment and expertise and improve open policies," he said regarding the 16th meeting of the central group on deepening overall reform.
Promoting opening-up in emerging reforms will give new impetus and vitality, it will also provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The lead group adopted a number of directives, including a negative list of regulatory market access, a relaxation of the border control policy, support for state-owned enterprises (SOEs) to absorb private capital, and a reorganisation of the registration resident system.
The declaration states that a negative list will be drawn up identifying sectors and businesses that are outside the investment limits.
This system will be gradually tested and improved through testing programs.
The move is significant because it will give the market a greater role in resource allocation, provide a legal business environment and make the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also release controls on the powers it delegates to companies and make sure that the companies themselves decide how to run their business.
The statement also said China would allow border regions to discover new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to support regional growth.
In an effort to open up state-controlled industries, more areas will be open to private investment.
"The government will not change its policy on foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of companies that are financed from abroad and will provide better services to them," the statement said.
In addition, it will be easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or a "green card," thanks to optimizing the requirements and simplifying the application process.
Ensuring lawyers' rights to practice and develop professional judges and prosecutors was also discussed at the meeting.
Prime Minister Li Keqiang and leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli also attended the meeting, according to a statement issued after the meeting.
New bed wards may be created in the Karlovy Vary Region.
According to Deputy Governor of the Karlovy Vary Region Jakub Pánik (Czech Social Democratic Party - ČSSD), the current capacity of the wards of two regional hospitals and two private hospitals in the region is sufficient and partial adjustments should be made on the basis of an agreement between the wards of individual hospitals.
There are also opportunities to expand care.
For example, in the department of surgical departments, one-day surgery centers could be established, where surgical procedures would be performed according to the set concept, which do not require hospitalization for more than 24 hours.
It is not yet clear in which specific hospitals a one-day surgery facility should be.
At the skin department of the Karlovy Vary hospital, a laser centre could be created with the possibility of using laser technology for skin diseases.
The concept also recommended the establishment of an apalic center to care for patients with brain disabilities who are in a vegetative state.
Such a center should be established centrally and should be an integral part of the anesthesiology-resuscitation department.
There is also the possibility of concentrating such a device in the hospital Ostrov, where similar care already exists.
Another bed capacity, which seems to be insufficient in the Karlovy Vary region, are the beds of follow-up care, especially the beds of the Long-Term Care Center (LDN), whose capacity in Nejdek is insufficient and, above all, should be closely linked to the acute care beds.
Part of this device should function as rehabilitation beds and part as classic LDN beds, the concept recommends.
As he points out, aftercare beds are missing mainly in the Karlovy Vary hospital.
There, abandoned buildings could be used after centralization.
Last but not least, the Karlovy Vary region lacks social health beds with a focus on the treatment of Alzheimer’s disease.
There is a shortage of these beds throughout the country, so it could also serve as a so-called Alzheimer center for other regions.
According to the recommendations, hospitals should also prepare for the introduction of so-called follow-up beds, for which European subsidies will be released.
"These are beds that will be linked to the areas of supesspecialized care and will form a space for the translation of patients after the procedure, for example, after cardiac surgery, neurosurgery, transplantation or other surgery," describes the regional concept of in-patient care.
New services could also be offered in the field of psychiatric care.
